# Steps to reproduce the problem
The width of the flex-wrap element should be 170px, not 150px.
Example link: https://codepen.io/vcxldk/pen/NWmLZQO
code:
```html
<html>
  <body>
     <div class="container">
  <div class="flex-wrap">
    <div class="box">1 50*50</div>
    <div class="box">2 50*50</div>
    <div class="box">3 50*50</div>
    <div class="box">4 50*50</div>
    <div class="box">5 50*50</div>
    <div class="box">6 50*50</div>
  </div>
</div>
<style>
.container {
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  position: relative;
}

.flex-wrap {
  position: absolute;

  width: max-content;
  height: 100%;

  box-sizing: content-box;
  background-color: gray;

  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  flex-direction: column;
  column-gap: 10px;
}

.box {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  border: solid 1px black;
  color: white;
}
</style>
</body>
<html>
```

# Problem Description
When using the following CSS attribute at the same time, the width of the elastic container cannot be stretched properly by the quilt element and the column gap:
- width: max-content;
- display: flex;
- flex-direction: column;
- column-gap: 10px;
- flex-wrap: wrap;

# Summary
Abnormal width when using "flex-wrap: wrap", "width: max-content" and "column-gap" at the same time

# Additional Data
Category: Content \
Chrome Channel: Stable \
Regression: N/A

I am trying to implement the following:

```java
// MyBridge.java
interface Natives {
  void myMethod(@JniType("std::vector") Object[] objectList);
}
```

```cpp
// my_bridge.cpp
static void JNI_MyBridge_MyMethod(
    JNIEnv* env,
    std::vector<jni_zero::ScopedJavaLocalRef<jobject>>& objectList);
```

However I get the following error:
```
../../third_party/jni_zero/jni_zero.h:765:14: error: no viable conversion from returned value of type 'const JavaRef<_jobject *>' to function return type 'ElementType' (aka 'jni_zero::ScopedJavaLocalRef<_jobject *>')
  765 |       return j_element;
```

This occurs because `ScopedJavaLocalRef(const JavaRef<T>& other)` is explicit and the failing line of code is trying to do an implicit conversion. Removing the explicit keyword or changing the methods argument type to `ScopedJavaLocalRef` removes the error.
